1

00:00:00,000  -->  00:00:01,820
In this next section,

2

00:00:01,820  -->  00:00:04,000
we'll be learning about typecasting,

3

00:00:04,000  -->  00:00:09,360
which is just a fancy word for converting a value from one data type to another.

4

00:00:09,360  -->  00:00:13,400
This is useful when you need to perform operations between different types.

5

00:00:13,400  -->  00:00:17,400
Example, if we wanted to count the number of fruits in your shopping cart.

6

00:00:17,400  -->  00:00:20,420
We'll use integers, whole numbers to do this.

7

00:00:20,420  -->  00:00:22,720
However, the names of the fruits,

8

00:00:22,720  -->  00:00:24,860
such as banana, apple,

9

00:00:24,860  -->  00:00:27,695
watermelon, orange, grapefruit,

10

00:00:27,695  -->  00:00:31,160
and so on, are strings and not numbers.

11

00:00:31,160  -->  00:00:34,320
If we tried to count strings, we can do that.

12

00:00:34,320  -->  00:00:37,800
But if we tried to add the name of a number,

13

00:00:37,800  -->  00:00:41,070
that just won't work because they are different entities,

14

00:00:41,070  -->  00:00:44,040
numbers are not the same as strings.

15

00:00:44,040  -->  00:00:49,185
When would we need to convert a value from one data type to another?

16

00:00:49,185  -->  00:00:51,570
Let's review some common scenarios.

17

00:00:51,570  -->  00:00:53,080
In terms of typecasting,

18

00:00:53,080  -->  00:00:57,580
let's talk about converting to an integer with the int function.

19

00:00:57,580  -->  00:01:00,480
Let's say you need to perform operations with

20

00:01:00,480  -->  00:01:04,440
values that are currently strings representing numbers.

21

00:01:04,440  -->  00:01:09,480
Strings that represent numbers can't be used directly in calculations. Think about it.

22

00:01:09,480  -->  00:01:16,220
Could you add multiple or divide two words of a sentence together?

23

00:01:16,220  -->  00:01:20,540
Words can't work like a number in a numeric equation.

24

00:01:20,540  -->  00:01:22,980
We need to convert them to integers first.

25

00:01:22,980  -->  00:01:28,835
To do this, we'll use the int function to convert a string to an integer.

26

00:01:28,835  -->  00:01:32,735
Let's see an example of something like this.

27

00:01:32,735  -->  00:01:35,490
We'll create a variable A,

28

00:01:35,490  -->  00:01:39,040
and we'll set that equal to a string of one, two, three.

29

00:01:39,040  -->  00:01:41,690
Then we're going to create a variable called B,

30

00:01:41,690  -->  00:01:47,530
and we're going to use the int function to turn A into an integer.

31

00:01:47,530  -->  00:01:52,930
We'll print B, and then we'll see what is created,

32

00:01:52,930  -->  00:01:56,850
can you guess what the output of B is going to be if we print this?

33

00:01:56,850  -->  00:02:00,950
If you guessed 123 as a number, you're right.

34

00:02:00,950  -->  00:02:04,230
If we were to try to check the type of B,

35

00:02:04,230  -->  00:02:06,240
let's see what that would be.

36

00:02:06,240  -->  00:02:09,585
If we do print and we do type,

37

00:02:09,585  -->  00:02:13,510
we put B in there, and then we hold on shift press Enter.

38

00:02:13,510  -->  00:02:17,690
We'll see that the class of the data type is integer.

39

00:02:17,690  -->  00:02:21,310
Now, if we were to do this same operation,

40

00:02:21,310  -->  00:02:26,120
but check A, what do you think the data type would be for A?

41

00:02:26,120  -->  00:02:27,840
If you said string, you're right.

42

00:02:27,840  -->  00:02:30,240
That's how we're able to turn A,

43

00:02:30,240  -->  00:02:33,200
which is a string into B,

44

00:02:33,200  -->  00:02:34,865
which is an integer.

45

00:02:34,865  -->  00:02:40,260
B is transformed into an integer or a number value while A remains a string,

46

00:02:40,260  -->  00:02:45,000
a series of characters united by quotation marks, like we see here.

47

00:02:45,000  -->  00:02:48,260
If we want to then test the data type of B,

48

00:02:48,260  -->  00:02:51,140
the last line will print that class integer,

49

00:02:51,140  -->  00:02:54,560
which confirms for us that we did this correctly,

50

00:02:54,560  -->  00:02:56,200
and variable B is, in fact,

51

00:02:56,200  -->  00:02:59,000
now an integer and not a string any longer.

52

00:02:59,000  -->  00:03:02,900
Let's see another example of using the int function in action,

53

00:03:02,900  -->  00:03:05,320
this time with user inputs.

54

00:03:05,320  -->  00:03:08,780
We'll be converting inputs more in-depth in the next section.

55

00:03:08,780  -->  00:03:11,940
But for now, just know that the input function is a way to

56

00:03:11,940  -->  00:03:16,120
prompt a user or viewer to put in a value like a Popa box,

57

00:03:16,120  -->  00:03:19,410
and then Python stores at value the user entered.

58

00:03:19,410  -->  00:03:22,880
Imagine you have a user input their age as a string,

59

00:03:22,880  -->  00:03:27,840
but you need to perform some quick calculations to figure out their age next year.

60

00:03:27,840  -->  00:03:29,740
To do this in Python,

61

00:03:29,740  -->  00:03:40,040
we'll first start a new cell and we'll say age string equals input, enter your age.

62

00:03:40,040  -->  00:03:46,260
This is going to allow an input field to pop up one we call age string,

63

00:03:46,260  -->  00:03:48,340
and that's going to show a prompt,

64

00:03:48,340  -->  00:03:49,640
which says enter your age,

65

00:03:49,640  -->  00:03:51,900
and that will allow for an input from the user.

66

00:03:51,900  -->  00:03:58,555
Then age integer or age int is going to equal the integer of age.

67

00:03:58,555  -->  00:04:01,100
Strings. Whatever the user inputs,

68

00:04:01,100  -->  00:04:03,690
we're going to automatically turn that into an integer.

69

00:04:03,690  -->  00:04:08,640
Next, age next year is going to equal age int plus one,

70

00:04:08,640  -->  00:04:13,960
because this will be whatever the user inputs turned into an integer plus one value,

71

00:04:13,960  -->  00:04:15,340
which is their age next year.

72

00:04:15,340  -->  00:04:18,820
We'll go ahead and print the value once we receive that,

73

00:04:18,820  -->  00:04:20,830
and we'll say next year,

74

00:04:20,830  -->  00:04:22,910
you will be,

75

00:04:22,910  -->  00:04:27,160
we'll take age next year because we're using a F string,

76

00:04:27,160  -->  00:04:30,220
passing that variable as a temp literal,

77

00:04:30,220  -->  00:04:31,800
and then say years old.

78

00:04:31,800  -->  00:04:36,160
We'll close that out with quotations, close the parenthesis.

79

00:04:36,160  -->  00:04:38,660
So let's review what we have so far.

80

00:04:38,660  -->  00:04:41,340
First, we'll want the user to enter their age,

81

00:04:41,340  -->  00:04:43,375
which we have with this input field.

82

00:04:43,375  -->  00:04:47,020
Let's say they put in 30 as a string into the textbox.

83

00:04:47,020  -->  00:04:50,720
When the variable age int is declared,

84

00:04:50,720  -->  00:04:53,800
we want to make sure that age string is

85

00:04:53,800  -->  00:04:57,420
an integer so that we can do math operations on it.

86

00:04:57,420  -->  00:04:59,840
Can you guess what would happen if a user inputs

87

00:04:59,840  -->  00:05:04,260
the word apple or 30 with quotes into the text box?

88

00:05:04,260  -->  00:05:12,065
If we were to use Apple as our input into this text box and press ''Enter'',

89

00:05:12,065  -->  00:05:17,165
we'll get invalid literal four int with base 10 apple.

90

00:05:17,165  -->  00:05:22,290
Let's try this again. What if we tried to put 10 into this?

91

00:05:22,290  -->  00:05:27,365
We'll also get invalid literal four int with base 10.

92

00:05:27,365  -->  00:05:30,410
We need to make sure that what we put into the value

93

00:05:30,410  -->  00:05:33,810
of age string is a number for this very reason.

94

00:05:33,810  -->  00:05:38,910
With the int function, we extract the value out of age string,

95

00:05:38,910  -->  00:05:40,655
which is what we put in here,

96

00:05:40,655  -->  00:05:42,930
and set it as an integer.

97

00:05:42,930  -->  00:05:46,750
In this way, when we set age next year,

98

00:05:46,750  -->  00:05:49,430
right here, in this next variable,

99

00:05:49,430  -->  00:05:53,250
we take the integer value of age int since we know it,

100

00:05:53,250  -->  00:05:55,830
and it must be an integer,

101

00:05:55,830  -->  00:05:57,770
and then add plus one to it,

102

00:05:57,770  -->  00:06:00,470
incrementing it by a value of one.

103

00:06:00,470  -->  00:06:03,830
When we ultimately print the value of the next year's statement,

104

00:06:03,830  -->  00:06:07,210
that will be the value of the users enter age plus one.

105

00:06:07,210  -->  00:06:11,370
If we put in 30 into this textbox,

106

00:06:11,370  -->  00:06:13,690
can you guess what the final output would be?

107

00:06:13,690  -->  00:06:18,415
If you said next year you will be 31 years old,

108

00:06:18,415  -->  00:06:21,460
then you're correct. Great work.
